State Hospital for the Insane - Operating Room inside a completely abandoned Surgical Building. Much to people’s dismay I’ve never had any ghost encounters in my tenure exploring. Always animals…. However on this morning I got into this building at around 4am in the pitch black. All I could hear were footsteps above me. Security was parked right out front of the building so that eliminated the possibility of it being a worker as he was sitting in the driver seat. My cat is heavy footed and I can hear him a floor up in my house, so perhaps it was a Godzilla sized raccoon roaming the halls above. Either way it was an odd and unnerving experience. Ended up hiding on a patient porch for roughly an hour until the sun came up and the sounds disappeared completely. I haven’t stepped foot in an insane asylum this year cause I’ve been so damn busy with my new land and ironically the hiatus is starting to drive me a bit kookoo. The paint peeling halls are calling…. and I shall heed the call. 👻 #asylums

33. Time flies when you are having fun. This was one of the biggest years for me in terms of “life changing” circumstances. I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again… If you told me a year ago that I’d own 20+ acres of land and a beautiful cat I would have laughed in your face. Life is weird though and can change in a matter of moments. The best thing we can do is go with the flow and follow our hearts. I’m not sure what the future holds but I’m confident if I continue following my heart… everything will be alright. I am especially thankful for my incredible family, girlfriend and my best friends. Good company is everything. If you read all this you probably genuinely support my art and endeavors and for that I thank you! Do me a favor and watch todays Episode of OtterCamp! Onward and upward folks! #otrcmp 🎂🎈Link in Bio 🦦

Traversing the depths of an active psychiatric facility. Otherwise known as an “Insane Asylum” in times of past. The beauty of these once self sustaining properties is that most of the buildings are generally connected by intricate tunnel systems. These tunnels served as infrastructure for steam heat, electrical conduit and transportation of goods and even sometimes patients. I’ve done some pretty crazy shit in the pursuit of seeing where “crazy” people were kept and ironically it’s one of my biggest saving graces for staying “Sane”. I spent 4 days on this campus by myself creeping to and fro underground whilst security, patients and workers alike were going about their day. At one point I found an exit hatch in the tunnel system and I heard rock music coming from the other side. It wasn’t the smartest idea but I popped my head up only to realize my head was emerging from the floor of an active laundry building. In that moment I felt like I was in a movie. I could picture the shot of a worker walking by singing and holding clothes only to look down and see my big head sticking out of a hatch in the floor. I’m thankful for these experiences… I grew up watching way to many adventure movies to sit at home as an adult and not do rad shit. Haven’t posted much photography as of late so figured I’d start sharing some more stuff. Just trying to keep my head above water. 🌊 #asylums #mentalhealth #abandoned

Five photos from five vastly different places. Haven’t shared much of my photography as of late and am making a conscious effort to share more this year. Comment which photo speaks to you the most if you feel so inclined.

1. An abandoned and overgrown jail on a Caribbean island. Low key Angkor Wat vibes. The roots were incredible. A place that truly feels ancient.

2. Underwater shot of the crystal clear glorious waters of Lahaina, Maui from 2022 surf shoot with @hi5sfoundation 

3. A private boat tour through the canals of Amsterdam on a warm summer night. There is no place I’d rather be. Truly the coziest and quaintest city I’ve ever experienced. Part of my heart will always be in Amsterdam.

4. A dilapidated and frozen granite quarry of times past. One of my escapes from the world. A place I will always hold dear to my heart.

5. A dark and creepy hydrotherapy chamber in the basement of a now demolished historic insane asylum. People once were sequestered in these rooms and secured into these tubs for what was considered “therapeutic” treatment at the time.

Can’t help but to feel nostalgic today. Second round of the 2024 Supercross season will kick off in San Francisco and it’s bringing back so many good memories. I moved to California in 2011 with all my belongings crammed into my car and a dream of working for GoPro. Its a long story but ultimately I got the opportunity to start working with the company shooting Supercross. Little did I know this would set the framework for my career today. No college education just a dollar and a dream…! 

Here are some of my favorite photos and memories from it all. Myself and @willposey821 got to work with many legends in the sport and really pushed the creative bounds on what was possible with a GoPro capturing Motocross. I will cherish these memories forever and I hope to make more in the future. Check out the last slide! A K-Tek “Norbert” rig with 4 GoPro 3+s on it. Talk about a throwback. If you have never ridden a dirtbike… change that. Throttle therapy is life! 👊🏼✊🏼🔥 #gopro #supercross #motocross
